SUMMARY:ENVS Colloquium Series Talk MacKay Jenkins
DESCRIPTION:Organized by: ['Environmental Studies']\\nCategory: Lecture/Pan
 el Discussion\\nEnvironmental Studies Program 2026 Colloquium Series 
  Talk by: McKay Jenkins       Date:  Monday\, April 6th\, 2026 Ti
 me:  12:30 pm - 1:30 pm (please note the changed time!)    (Bring you
 r lunch)  Location:  SCI Cunniff (SC 199)Title:  "The Praxis of Enviro
 nmental Justice: Working Ethically with University Students and Community 
 Partners" For the past twenty years\, my University of Delaware students h
 ave been training in environmental and community engagement efforts\, work
 ing with regional Black and Native American partners. This includes field-
 based research in everything from the cultural and historical (learning st
 ructures of economic disempowerment and environmental degradation) to clin
 ical techniques of ecological restoration work (building community greenho
 uses\; growing food on urban farms\; learning to identify native and invas
 ive plants\; learning to repair of garden soils) to the creative and schol
 arly (how to create pieces of journalism\, advocacy writing\, or grant pro
 posals). South of UD’s campus\, Baltimore City offers broad opportunitie
 s to study\, support and learn from community work in ecological restorati
 on and community building\, especially through urban reforestation and foo
 d security. McKay Jenkins is a writer\, professor\, restoration ecologist
  and urban farmer. He has published nine books and many articles and essay
 s about the natural world and social justice. His book The Maryland Natur
 alist (Johns Hopkins University Press\, 2024) is a collection of natural 
 history essays that serves as the primary text for the Maryland State Mast
 er Naturalist Certification Program. His book The Delaware Naturalist Han
 dbook (University of Delaware Press\, 2020\, co-edited with Susan Barton)
 \, serves as the primary text for the Delaware State Master Naturalist Cer
 tification Program. Jenkins other books include Food Fight: GMOs and the 
 Future of the American Diet (Avery\, 2017)\; Poison Spring: The Secret H
 istory of Pollution and the EPA (co-authored with Evaggelos Vallianatos) 
 (Bloomsbury\, 2014)\; and ContamiNation: My Quest to Survive in a Toxic W
 orld (Avery\, 2016)\, originally published as What’s Gotten Into Us: S
 taying Healthy in a Toxic World (Random House\, 2011)\, which chronicled 
 his investigation into the myriad synthetic chemicals we encounter in our 
 daily lives\, and the growing body of evidence about the harm these chemic
 als do to our bodies and the environment. Jenkins holds degrees from Amhe
 rst\, Columbia’s Graduate School of Journalism\, and Princeton\, where h
 e received a PhD in English. A former staff writer for the Atlanta Constit
 ution\, he has also written for Outside\, Orion\, The New Republic\, and m
 any other publications. Jenkins is currently the Cornelius Tilghman Profe
 ssor of English\, Journalism and Environmental Humanities at UD\, where h
 e has won the University Excellence in Teaching Award and both the Excelle
 nce in Teaching Award and the Outstanding Scholarship Award from the Coll
 ege of Arts and Sciences. He oversees the Rock Rose Food Justice Project\,
  an urban farm in Baltimore\, where he lives with his family. Co-Sponsore
 d by the Environmental Studies Program and the Mellon Foundation\\nDetails
 : https://swatcentral.swarthmore.edu/?trumbaEmbed=view%3Devent%26eventid%3
 D1384936412
LOCATION:Science Center Room 199-Cunniff Hall Tiered Classroom
URL:https://swatcentral.swarthmore.edu/?trumbaEmbed=view%3Devent%26eventid%
 3D1384936412
CATEGORIES:Lecture/Panel Discussion
END:VEVENT
