SUMMARY:Writing Cross Cultures\, Working Between Languages: The Translation
 al Prism of Taiwan
DESCRIPTION:Organized by: ['Chinese'\, 'Asian Studies'\, 'Comparative Liter
 ature'\, 'Global Studies Program'\, 'Japanese'\, 'Modern Languages and Lit
 eratures'\, 'Russian']\\nCategory: Lecture/Panel Discussion\\nThis talk ex
 plores the intricate histories and human connections embedded in contempor
 ary Taiwanese literature—works that strive to reclaim forbidden memories
  and navigate the identity of a multilingual\,immigrant society. Using tra
 nslation as a "prism\," we will examine the diverse facets of Taiwanese cu
 lture and the power of literary translation to capture the subtle nuances 
 of shifting linguistic practices. Featuring Lin King Lin King is an acclai
 med writer and translator from Taiwan. A 2018 winner of the PEN/Robert J. 
 Dau Short Story Prize\, she reached a career milestone in 2024 as a winner
  of the National Book Award for Translated Literature. Joining us to discu
 ss the challenges and promises of the craft\, she will focus on three of h
 er major translated works: Taiwan Travelogue: A Novel\, The Boy from Clear
 water\, and A Perfect Day to Put Your Head into the Oven.Sponsored by Mode
 rn Languages and Literatures (Chinese\, Japanese and Russian Sections)\, A
 sian Studies\, Comparative Literature and Global Studies Contact: Claire L
 i\; cli3@swarthmore.edu\\nDetails: https://swatcentral.swarthmore.edu/?tru
 mbaEmbed=view%3Devent%26eventid%3D1376027666
LOCATION:Kohlberg Hall Scheuer Room - Multi-Purpose Room
URL:https://swatcentral.swarthmore.edu/?trumbaEmbed=view%3Devent%26eventid%
 3D1376027666
CATEGORIES:Lecture/Panel Discussion
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:4f61758c3b44183a@swarthmore-dash-calendar
DTSTAMP:20260406T115326Z
DTSTART:20260409T203000Z
DTEND:20260409T220000Z
SUMMARY:“Storying the ‘Land of Fires’: Feminist and Disabled Politica
 l Ecologies of Environmental Justice in Southern Italy”
DESCRIPTION:Organized by: ['Environmental Justice']\\nCategory: Lecture/Pan
 el Discussion\\n“Storying the ‘Land of Fires’: Feminist and Disable
 d Political Ecologies of Environmental Justice in Southern Italy” Dr. Il
 enia Iengo\, Postdoctoral Researcher\, Disabled Ecologies Lab\, UC Berkele
 y In this talk\, Iengo explores her scholar-activist approach to feminist 
 and disabled political ecological praxis\, weaving together knowledges\, p
 ractices\, and imaginaries emerging from social and environmental justice 
 organizing in the ‘Land of Fires’ (Terra dei Fuochi) in Campania\, Ita
 ly.  ‘Land of Fires’ refers to the region in southern Italy that has 
 been the site of decades of illegal toxic dumping and burning\, resulting 
 in air and water contamination and disproportionately high rates of cancer
 \, reproductive disorders\, and other environmental illnesses.  Grounded 
 in the lived experiences of sacrificed and marginalized communities\, Ieng
 o argues that storytelling becomes a powerful tool for political organizin
 g and consciousness-raising. It invites us to critically examine the ablei
 st\, heteronormative\, and neoliberal frameworks that shape dominant under
 standings of health\, nature\, and justice\, while also opening space for 
 the transformative possibilities of collective care\, mutual aid\, and int
 erdependence among bodies and territories.\\nDetails: https://swatcentral.
 swarthmore.edu/?trumbaEmbed=view%3Devent%26eventid%3D1386268986
LOCATION:Kohlberg Room 115-Classroom
URL:https://swatcentral.swarthmore.edu/?trumbaEmbed=view%3Devent%26eventid%
 3D1386268986
CATEGORIES:Lecture/Panel Discussion
END:VEVENT
