BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:11be567cad741a07@swarthmore-dash-calendar
DTSTAMP:20260406T115326Z
DTSTART:20260412T000000Z
DTEND:20260412T030000Z
SUMMARY:"AI and the Future of Humanity" : A Night Owls Event with Chloé Ba
 kalar (AI Ethics Lead at Open AI) and Jonny Thakkar
DESCRIPTION:Organized by: ['Political Science'\, 'Philosophy']\\nCategory: 
 Lecture/Panel Discussion\\nPlease join Chloé Bakalar and Jonny Thakkar on
  Saturday April 11th\, from 8pm to 11pm in SCI 199\, for a Night Owls eve
 nt on “AI and the Future of Humanity”. As artificial intelligence mode
 ls become more and more powerful\, it is hard not to feel some degree of 
 panic. The value of the skills we have worked so hard to acquire\, the ach
 ievements we have worked so hard to accomplish\, the institutions we have
  worked so hard to build—all that seems to be threatened with irrelevan
 ce or extinction. What will the future look like for humanity in a world 
 dominated by AI? Or is that the wrong way of framing things? And howmuch o
 f this is hype anyway? To discuss these questions\, along with a myriad of
  ethical dilemmas associated with the development of artificial intellige
 nce\, we are extraordinarily fortunate to be able to welcome Chloé Bakal
 ar\, AI Ethics Lead at Open AI. Before entering the tech world\, Chloé wa
 s a political and legal theorist. She received her PhD from Penn in 2014 
 and completed a postdoc at Princeton before becoming an assistant profess
 or at Temple in 2018. In 2019 she then became Chief Ethicist at Meta\, wh
 ere she developed and lead an applied ethics program focused on Meta’s 
 family of AI-powered platforms\, products and systems\, before joining Ope
 n AI in 2025. As a reminder\, the Night Owls series consists of nocturnal 
 philosophical discussions of questions that are central to the lives of s
 tudents and faculty. The format involves an initial discussion with Jonny
  Thakkar\, Associate Professor of Political Science\, followed by an open 
 Q&A. Cookies and coffee are provided. So far we have hosted Agnes Callard
  on "Is Ambition Ugly?"\, Krista Thomason on "Why Bad Feelings Make Life 
 Good"\, Sa'ed Atshan on "Pacifism"\, Vincent Lloydon "What Makes a Good Pr
 otest?"\, Nikil Saval on "Becoming a Politician"\, Annie Stilz on “Can a
  People Own Land?”\, Daniel Wodak on “What Does Democracy Actually Me
 an?”\, Anastasia Berg on “What Are Children For?”\, Musa Al-Gharbi 
 on “What Was Wokeness?”\, Peter Baumann on “Would Immortality Be Go
 od?” and Becca Rothfeld on “Making Yourself Beautiful”.  This event
  is sponsored by Philosophy\, Political Science and The Point magazine.\\n
 Details: https://swatcentral.swarthmore.edu/?trumbaEmbed=view%3Devent%26ev
 entid%3D1384783043
LOCATION:Science Center Room 101- Chang Hou Hall Tiered Classroom
URL:https://swatcentral.swarthmore.edu/?trumbaEmbed=view%3Devent%26eventid%
 3D1384783043
CATEGORIES:Lecture/Panel Discussion
END:VEVENT
