SUMMARY:"Literary Life Histories: Reclaiming Reading and Living the Story" 
 Book Talk
DESCRIPTION:Organized by: ['Educational Studies']\\nCategory: Lecture/Panel
  Discussion\\nPlease join us for a book talk with Drs. Susan Browne\, Vala
 rie G. Lee and Marjorie E. Madden. Literary Life Histories: Reclaiming Rea
 ding and Living the Story speaks to literacy instruction and practices ac
 ross a large span that includes upper elementary through university classr
 ooms. The book looks at the intersection of comprehension\, engagement an
 d culture in literacy education. Through an innovative framework of liter
 ary life histories — Read\, Interpret\, Script\, Perform — students e
 xplore the intertextuality of character and culture in texts and learn t
 o think more deeply and compassionately about the world. This book shows
  middle and high school teachers and college instructors how to engage s
 tudents in immersive reading using critical\, multicultural texts that ul
 timately culminates in rich dramatic performances.\\nDetails: https://swa
 tcentral.swarthmore.edu/?trumbaEmbed=view%3Devent%26eventid%3D1380607297
LOCATION:Singer Hall Room 033 - Tiered Classroom
URL:https://swatcentral.swarthmore.edu/?trumbaEmbed=view%3Devent%26eventid%
 3D1380607297
CATEGORIES:Lecture/Panel Discussion
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:29e3d11a9097b1ef@swarthmore-dash-calendar
DTSTAMP:20260406T115326Z
DTSTART:20260413T203000Z
DTEND:20260413T213000Z
SUMMARY:Dresden Lecture
DESCRIPTION:Organized by: ['Mathematics and Statistics']\\nCategory: Lectur
 e/Panel Discussion\\nMonday\, April 134:15pm Refreshments\; Lecture 4:30-5
 :30pmThe Gibbs Phenomenon: a 100 year adventureWhen we try to approximate 
 a function using waves—like sines and cosines—we expect that adding mo
 re and more waves will give a better and better match (much like how addi
 ng more and more polynomials can give a better fit). Surprisingly\, this i
 s not always the case! Near sharp jumps or edges\, the approximation devel
 ops ripples that persist no matter how many waves we include. This puzzlin
 g behavior\, now known as the Gibbs phenomenon\, was first noticed in the 
 1800s\, and was the subject of a spirited discussion in a letter to Natu
 re in 1898. In this talk\, we will explore the history of the Gibbs phenom
 enon. We will try to understand why these oscillations occur and what they
  tell us about the limits of representing complicated signals using smooth
  building blocks. Along the way\, we will connect this phenomenon to famil
 iar ideas such as image compression\, audio signals\, and the appearance o
 f ringing artifacts. We will then discuss how mathematicians have learned 
 to reduce or control these oscillations.  This talk requires no specializ
 ed background and aims to give an intuitive understanding of a phenomenon 
 that sits at the intersection of mathematics\, science\, and everyday tech
 nology. Tuesday\, April 144:15pm Refreshments\; Lecture 4:30-5:30pm Strong
  stability preserving methods for time-dependent problems When solving tim
 e-dependent problems on a computer—especially those involving sharp chan
 ges like shock waves or steep gradients—we want numerical methods that b
 ehave in a stable and reliable way. Strong stability preserving (SSP) Rung
 e–Kutta methods are designed to do exactly this: they help ensure that i
 mportant features of the solution\, such as avoiding spurious oscillations
 \, are maintained as the computation moves forward in time. In this talk\,
  we will introduce the basic ideas behind SSP methods and explain why they
  are useful in practice. We will also discuss some of the challenges in de
 signing these methods\, including limitations on how accurate or efficient
  they can be. Finally\, we will give a broad overview of different types o
 f SSP methods and how they are used\, highlighting both what is currently 
 possible and what questions remain open. The goal of this talk is to provi
 de an intuitive understanding of SSP methods and help students see how mod
 ern numerical analysis tackles real computational problems. This topic wil
 l be accessible to anyone who has taken Calculus and seen a differential e
 quation.\\nDetails: https://swatcentral.swarthmore.edu/?trumbaEmbed=view%3
 Devent%26eventid%3D1385106218
LOCATION:Science Center Room 101- Chang Hou Hall Tiered Classroom
URL:https://swatcentral.swarthmore.edu/?trumbaEmbed=view%3Devent%26eventid%
 3D1385106218
CATEGORIES:Lecture/Panel Discussion
END:VEVENT
