SUMMARY:Acting Up in Hopeless Times Sager Symposium
DESCRIPTION:Organized by: ['Gender and Sexuality Studies'\, 'Black Studies'
 \, 'English Literature'\, 'History'\, 'Intercultural Center'\, 'Lang Cente
 r for Civic & Social Responsil'\, 'Office of Inclusive Excellence'\, 'Peac
 e and Conflict Studies'\, 'SAGER Fund'\, 'Sociology and Anthropology'\, 'T
 heater'\, 'William J. Cooper Foundation']\\nCategory: Lecture/Panel Discus
 sion\\nActing Up in Hopeless Times Sager Symposium April 14 Kohlberg Hall\
 , Scheuer Room   Schedule of Events 9:55-11:10 a.m. - Panel 1:  Creating
  Protest/Resistance from Public Panic (Marlon Bailey\, Jamal Batts\, Salon
 ee Bhanam) + moderated Q&A2:40-3:55 p.m. - Panel 2: Queer Historical Imagi
 nation in Crisis (Debra Levine\, Dahlia Li\, Olivia Polk) + moderated Q&A
  7:00-9:30 p.m. - Activist Teach In and Q&A with ACT UP member\, Debra Le
 vinePlease RSVP for this event by 3:00 p.m. on April 7th. Acting Up in Hop
 eless Times convenes an intergenerational group of public intellectuals\, 
 community historians\, activists\, and scholars to consider the ongoing qu
 eer legacies of the 1980’s AIDS pandemic and ACT UP activism. This sympo
 sium puts the politically-dire situation of 2026 for LGBTQ+ individuals in
  continuity with the political histories begun and continued in the 1980
 ’s AIDS epidemic. By framing LGBTQ+ activism\, culture\, and community a
 s the direct result of political crisis\, rather than its pre-emption or r
 emedy\, this symposium aims to catalyze a renewal of 1) queer theory and h
 istoriography within scholarly and public discourses and 2) forms of queer
  civic and political life that have faltered since the discontinuities of 
 knowledge transfer created by COVID-19. This event is free\, accessible an
 d open to the public. To see full event details\, please visit our website
 .  To view the AccessAble USA guide for the Scheuer Room of Kohlberg Hall
  please click here. To view AccessAble USA for Swarthmore College\, please
  click this link.  For directions\, parking\, and a campus map\, please v
 isit https://www.swarthmore.edu/visit-swarthmore. For questions\, please c
 ontact kgomezz1@swarthmore.edu.   Presented with the support of Sager Fu
 nd\, William J. Cooper Foundation\, Clark Fund for Gender Discourse\, Lang
  Center for Civic and Social Responsibility\, The Swarthmore Office of Inc
 lusive Excellence  Cosponsored by Program in Gender and Sexuality Studies
 \, Swarthmore Intercultural Center\, Department of English\, Department of
  Black Studies\, Department of Theater\, Department of Peace and Conflict 
 Studies\, Department of Sociology and Anthropology\, Department of History
   \\nDetails: https://swatcentral.swarthmore.edu/?trumbaEmbed=view%3Deven
 t%26eventid%3D1382908716
URL:https://swatcentral.swarthmore.edu/?trumbaEmbed=view%3Devent%26eventid%
 3D1382908716
CATEGORIES:Lecture/Panel Discussion
END:VEVENT
