SUMMARY:Environmental Studies Program Colloquium Series: Kyle Whyte
DESCRIPTION:Organized by: ['Environmental Studies'\, 'Environmental Justice
 ']\\nCategory: Lecture/Panel Discussion\\nEnvironmental Studies Program
  2026 Colloquium Series Talk by: Kyle Whyte      Date:  Monday\, Ap
 ril 20th\, 2026 Time:  12:00 pm - 1:00 pm  (Bring your lunch)  Locat
 ion:  SCI Cunniff (SC 199)Title: "Why Does Anything Need to be Called Wi
 ld?" **The impacts of climate change and biodiversity loss are creating ex
 treme unease about the future of natural places. Moreover\, groups such as
  Indigenous peoples are facing some of the most acute harms. Yet\, is wild
 erness the best term to call these places? This presentation will discuss 
 why Indigenous peoples have alternative ways to conceptualize climate miti
 gation and biodiversity conservation that need not lean on the use of the 
 term "wilderness."  ** Kyle Whyte\, "Why Does Anything Need to be Calle
 d Wild?"\, In\, The Heart of the Wild: Essays on Nature\, Conservation\,
  and the Human Future\, edited by Ben A. Minteer and Jonathan B. Loso (P
 rinceton University Press\, 2024).   Kyle Whyte is the George Willis Pa
 ck Professor in the School for Environment and Sustainability and Universi
 ty Diversity and a Social Transformation Professor. He teaches in and coor
 dinates the School’s environmental justice graduate specialization. He i
 s founding Faculty Director of the Tishman Center for Social Justice and t
 he Environment\, Principal Investigator of the Environmental Justice + Hum
 anities Hub\, co-Principal Investigator of the Global Center for Climate C
 hange and Transboundary Waters\, Faculty Associate of Native American Stud
 ies\, Principal Investigator of the Secretariat for the Pathways Alliance 
 for Change and Transformation\, STRIDE Committee member\, affiliate Profes
 sor of Philosophy\, and Senior Fellow in the Michigan Society of Fellows.
  Whyte’s research on environmental justice centers on moral and politic
 al issues that Indigenous peoples are addressing in the areas of climate c
 hange\, conservation\, and cooperative relationships with science institut
 ions. He is an enrolled member of the Citizen Potawatomi Nation. His publi
 cations appear in journals including Climatic Change\, Weather\, Climate
  & Society\, Science\, Daedalus\, WIREs Climate Change\, Environment &
  Planning E\, and Sustainability Science. Co-sponsored by the Environmen
 tal Justice & Community Resilience Program at the Lang Center\, Environmen
 tal Studies Program\, Office of Sustainability and the Mellon Foundation.
   \\nDetails: https://swatcentral.swarthmore.edu/?trumbaEmbed=view%3Deve
 nt%26eventid%3D1386268987
LOCATION:Science Center Room 199-Cunniff Hall Tiered Classroom
URL:https://swatcentral.swarthmore.edu/?trumbaEmbed=view%3Devent%26eventid%
 3D1386268987
CATEGORIES:Lecture/Panel Discussion
END:VEVENT
