SUMMARY:Senior Lang Scholar Presentations
DESCRIPTION:Organized by: ['Lang Center for Civic & Social Responsil']\\nCa
 tegory: Conference\\nLaunched in the early 80s at Swarthmore College by Eu
 gene M. Lang ’38\, the Lang Opportunity Scholarship Program selects up t
 o six members of the sophomore class each year and provides them with an a
 rray of undergraduate and graduate benefits – including a $12k project g
 rant.  To date\, LOS has cultivated 100s of Lang Scholars who have partner
 ed with 100s more communities on projects all over the world. Join the LOS
  Class of 2026 to hear about their inspiring projects! They are: Mya Chulu
 undorj's project\, “Story-Capturers: The Voices of the Land\,” is a di
 gital archive preserving the cultural heritage of Mongolian rural communit
 ies\, engaging students against climate change and urbanization.  Lena H
 abtu created a documentary with Human Rights First Ethiopia highlighting T
 igrayans’ experiences during the 2020-2022 conflict.Prerna Karmacharya
 ’s project seeks to decrease the underrepresentation of blind and visual
 ly impaired individuals in STEM fields like robotics in partnership with P
 erkins School for the Blind. Steven Mukum’s project\, Rising Above Wate
 r\, addresses internal displacement in Dangbo\, Benin\, caused by climate-
 related flooding through training in sustainable agriculture and providing
  flood-resistant infrastructure in partnership with OJECC Bénin.Billy Wu
 ’s project\, Acquired Tomorrows\, reduces stigma and increases access to
  mental health with project partner\, Home for the Disabled Kunshan and Sh
 angXiang Counseling.\\nDetails: https://swatcentral.swarthmore.edu/?trumba
 Embed=view%3Devent%26eventid%3D1380668692
LOCATION:Lang Performing Arts Center Lobby (LPAC)\, Lang Performing Arts Ce
 nter Room (LPAC) 101 Cinema
URL:https://swatcentral.swarthmore.edu/?trumbaEmbed=view%3Devent%26eventid%
 3D1380668692
CATEGORIES:Conference
END:VEVENT
